pr_review_body:
@jackton1 thanks for the contribution (and for fixing this up and coordinating with #307)! This looks great to me for `gcloud-aio-storage`, we'll just need to fix it up for the `gcloud-rest-storage` build: since that version of the library is expected to not require async, we'll need to make sure `aiofiles` doesn't get used in that case.

You can see from the [build artifacts](https://app.circleci.com/pipelines/github/talkiq/gcloud-aio/1327/workflows/e52d46a9-533d-4d85-b1c6-aa949bc103ed/jobs/27143/artifacts) that `gcloud-rest-storage` would currently be broken here, since it would attempt to use `aiofiles` in a non-async fashion (and generally users of `gcloud-rest` are not able or do not want to use `asyncio` features).

I've added a couple comments as to how you might be able to tackle this!

At high level, I'm not sure if we should turn this on by default. If we do so, it may slow down the task scheduling when this failure happens.
But this is able to improve the stability when env issues happen indeed.
@ericl Thoughts?

@uliSchuster Thanks for working on this. There are some linting issue which need to be fixed (run flake8 or see CI). I have adjusted the changelog to clarify when this issue is encountered.
I am not too happy about changing an existing test for this but I know tests are currently messy. So I think this is fine for now and can be cleaned up with #468

@n2ygk As you have already started reviewing it I leave you with this to give the final call in terms of approval.

SGTM overall. 

But we need to decide when is the best time to save the port. 

@librasungirl has proposed to save the port when the first SRP client successfully registered a service, which I agree is the best strategy. 

Thoughts?

@superwhd @librasungirl @jwhui @wgtdkp @abtink

The changes on the C++ overall look good to me. I would advise testing them on FBcode and updating buck before merging to ensure we won't break anything internally.

My only concern, and it's not linked to this PR, is the amount of duplicate and boilerplate code we are forced to add in the repo to handle the registrations.

@ezyang I know that a year ago you've been working on improving the op registration. Is there a better way to do it?

A couple comments; 

1. Why are some of test assert values are changed?
2. Can you make sure we can copy the object ID spread to 2 lines by double clicking it? This is really important for UX.

One inline comment about maybe adding `.[test]`, but it currently works, so it is fine.

Let's try Jenkins again:

@jenkins-plone-org please run jobs

Please also add a unit test that fails without your fix and passes with your fix.

Something like this would work:
```python
@mb.program(input_specs=[mb.TensorSpec(shape=(10, 20))])
def prog(x):
    return mb.square(x=x, name="tensor")

ct.convert(prog, source="milinternal",
    convert_to="mlprogram", compute_precision=ct.precision.FLOAT32)
```

[test_programs.py](https://github.com/apple/coremltools/blob/main/coremltools/converters/mil/mil/tests/test_programs.py) is probably the best place for this test.
